const e={id:"febrile-neutropenia",name:"Febrile Neutropenia",icon:"🩻",category:"Infectious Disease",overview:{definition:"Febrile neutropenia (FN) is defined as a single oral temperature ≥38.3°C (101°F) OR a sustained temperature ≥38.0°C (100.4°F) for ≥1 hour in a patient with neutropenia (ANC <500 cells/μL, or ANC <1000 cells/μL with a predicted nadir of <500 cells/μL within 48 hours). FN is a medical emergency — untreated, gram-negative bacteremia in neutropenic patients carries mortality approaching 50% within 24–48 hours. Empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics must be started within 60 minutes of triage in high-risk patients. Risk stratification (MASCC score or CISNE score) guides the decision between outpatient oral therapy and inpatient IV antibiotics.",epidemiology:"FN occurs in approximately 10–50% of patients with solid tumors and >80% of patients with hematologic malignancies receiving intensive chemotherapy. Incidence is highest with AML induction therapy, allogeneic HSCT conditioning, and high-dose chemotherapy regimens. Mortality from FN has declined over decades due to risk stratification, empiric antipseudomonal therapy, antifungal prophylaxis, and G-CSF use — overall mortality is now 2–5% in low-risk patients and up to 10–20% in high-risk patients with documented bacteremia. Gram-positive organisms now account for 60–70% of documented bacteremias (largely due to indwelling catheters and mucositis), while gram-negatives — though less frequent — carry disproportionately high mortality and remain the primary empiric coverage target. Invasive fungal infections (IFI) emerge in patients with prolonged neutropenia (>7–10 days) and represent a second wave of infectious mortality.",keyGuidelines:[{name:"IDSA 2010 Febrile Neutropenia Guideline",detail:"The foundational US practice guideline for clinical assessment and antimicrobial management of FN. Key recommendations: (1) Risk stratification with MASCC score to identify low-risk patients eligible for outpatient oral therapy. (2) Antipseudomonal beta-lactam monotherapy (cefepime, piperacillin-tazobactam, or meropenem) as empiric first-line for high-risk FN. (3) Vancomycin NOT recommended routinely as empiric therapy — add only for specific indications. (4) Empiric antifungal therapy for persistent fever after 4–7 days of antibiotics. (5) Quinolone prophylaxis for high-risk patients with expected neutropenia >7 days. Despite being from 2010, this guideline remains the primary US reference.",sourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"]},{name:"NCCN 2024 Prevention and Treatment of Cancer-Related Infections",detail:"Comprehensive, annually updated guideline covering FN management, prophylaxis, and G-CSF use. NCCN 2024 updates include: refined risk stratification incorporating CISNE score for solid tumor patients, strengthened recommendations for posaconazole prophylaxis in AML/MDS patients, expanded OPAT criteria for low-risk FN, updated G-CSF primary prophylaxis thresholds (≥20% febrile neutropenia risk), and guidance on Clostridioides difficile prevention in patients receiving FQ prophylaxis. NCCN categorizes evidence as: Category 1 (high-level evidence + uniform NCCN consensus), Category 2A (lower-level evidence + uniform NCCN consensus), Category 2B (lower-level evidence + non-uniform NCCN consensus).",sourceIds:["nccn-fever-neutropenia"]},{name:"MASCC Risk Index (Multinational Association for Supportive Care in Cancer)",detail:"The MASCC score is the most validated risk stratification tool for FN. Maximum score = 26. Low risk = score ≥21 (associated with serious medical complication rate <10% and mortality <1%). High risk = score <21. Scoring variables: burden of illness (no or mild symptoms = 5, moderate symptoms = 3, severe symptoms = 0), no hypotension (5 points), no COPD (4 points), solid tumor or no prior fungal infection in hematologic malignancy (4 points), outpatient status at onset of fever (3 points), no dehydration (3 points), age <60 years (2 points). Low-risk patients (score ≥21) are candidates for oral step-down therapy and outpatient management after a period of IV observation and clinical assessment.",sourceIds:["mascc-risk-index"]},{name:"CISNE Score (Clinical Index of Stable Febrile Neutropenia)",detail:"An alternative risk stratification tool specifically validated in solid tumor outpatients with FN who clinically appear stable. CISNE scoring: ECOG PS ≥2 (2 points), stress-induced hyperglycemia (2 points), COPD (1 point), cardiovascular disease history (1 point), NCI mucositis grade ≥2 (1 point), monocytes <200/μL (1 point). CISNE 0 = very low risk (complication rate ~1.1%); CISNE 1–2 = low-intermediate risk (~6%); CISNE ≥3 = high risk (~36%). CISNE is complementary to MASCC — a patient can score low-risk on MASCC but high-risk on CISNE. NCCN 2024 recommends using CISNE in addition to MASCC for solid tumor patients.",sourceIds:["cisne-score"]},{name:"ASCO WBC Growth Factor Guideline Update (2015)",detail:"Foundational ASCO guidance for G-CSF prophylaxis. Primary prophylaxis is recommended when regimen-level FN risk is ≥20% or when intermediate-risk regimens are paired with important patient-specific risk factors. Secondary prophylaxis is recommended when preserving dose intensity matters and prior FN would otherwise force treatment compromise. Filgrastim and pegfilgrastim remain the core supportive-care agents.",sourceIds:["asco-2015-gcsf"]}],landmarkTrials:[{name:"Cordonnier et al. (2009) — Empirical vs Preemptive Antifungal Therapy",detail:"Randomized high-risk FN trial comparing the traditional empirical-antifungal strategy with a preemptive strategy triggered by imaging, galactomannan, or other fungal evidence. Preemptive therapy reduced antifungal exposure and costs but led to more probable/proven IFI, reinforcing why many high-risk hematology patients still receive empirical mold-active treatment after persistent fever rather than waiting for clearer fungal signals.",sourceIds:["cordonnier-2009-empirical-vs-preemptive"]},{name:"Winston et al. (2000, J Infect Dis) — Fluconazole vs Amphotericin B Empiric Antifungal",detail:"Randomized trial showing fluconazole could be an alternative to amphotericin B deoxycholate for selected neutropenic patients with persistent fever, with better tolerability but important mold-coverage limitations. The trial helped move practice away from reflexive conventional amphotericin B, but its applicability is narrow because fluconazole does not cover Aspergillus or other molds that dominate high-risk prolonged-neutropenia scenarios.",sourceIds:["winston-2000-empiric-antifungal"]},{name:"Walsh et al. (NEJM 1999) — Liposomal Amphotericin B vs Conventional AmB for Empiric Antifungal",detail:"RCT demonstrating that liposomal amphotericin B (AmBisome 3 mg/kg/day) was equivalent in efficacy to conventional amphotericin B for empiric antifungal therapy in neutropenic patients with persistent fever, with significantly less nephrotoxicity (19% vs 34% infusion reactions, 19% vs 34% creatinine doubling). Established liposomal formulations as preferred when amphotericin B is needed. However, this was pre-echinocandin era.",sourceIds:["walsh-1999-lamb-vs-amb"]},{name:"Walsh et al. (NEJM 2004) — Caspofungin vs Liposomal Amphotericin B for Empiric Antifungal",detail:"RCT demonstrating caspofungin was non-inferior to liposomal amphotericin B for empiric antifungal therapy in FN patients. Caspofungin had better overall success (33.9% vs 33.7%) with significantly better tolerability. This trial, combined with the micafungin data, established echinocandins as an alternative to liposomal amphotericin B for empiric antifungal therapy in FN, particularly when Candida is more likely than Aspergillus.",sourceIds:["walsh-2004-caspofungin"]},{name:"Freifeld et al. (NEJM 1999) — Oral vs IV Antibiotics for Low-Risk FN",detail:"RCT (IDSA-sponsored) of ciprofloxacin + amoxicillin-clavulanate PO vs ceftriaxone + amikacin IV for low-risk FN. Oral combination was equally effective (success rates 71% vs 67%, p=NS) with similar safety. This trial established the evidence base for oral outpatient management of low-risk FN and directly informed the IDSA 2010 guideline recommendation for ciprofloxacin + amoxicillin-clavulanate as first-line oral therapy for low-risk patients.",sourceIds:["freifeld-1999-low-risk-fn"]},{name:"Kern et al. (NEJM 1999) — Oral vs IV Empirical Therapy",detail:"EORTC multicenter RCT showing that hospitalized low-risk febrile neutropenic patients treated with oral ciprofloxacin plus amoxicillin-clavulanate had outcomes equivalent to IV ceftriaxone plus amikacin. This reinforced the oral-combination strategy for carefully selected low-risk FN and complemented the contemporaneous Freifeld trial.",sourceIds:["kern-1999-low-risk-fn"]},{name:"GIMEMA/EORTC — Antifungal Prophylaxis Trials (Cornely et al., NEJM 2007)",detail:"Landmark RCT establishing posaconazole superiority over fluconazole/itraconazole for antifungal prophylaxis in AML/MDS patients receiving remission induction or salvage chemotherapy. Posaconazole reduced IFI (2% vs 8%, p<0.001), invasive aspergillosis (1% vs 7%, p<0.001), and IFI-related mortality (1% vs 4%, p=0.046). This trial directly led to posaconazole becoming the preferred prophylactic antifungal for high-risk AML/MDS patients in IDSA, NCCN, and ECIL guidelines.",sourceIds:["cornely-2007-posaconazole"]},{name:"Wingard et al. (Blood 2010) — Voriconazole vs Fluconazole Prophylaxis in Allogeneic HSCT",detail:"RCT in allogeneic HSCT recipients. Voriconazole reduced invasive aspergillosis vs. fluconazole (1.5% vs 3%, p=0.02) and improved 180-day fungal infection-free survival. However, no significant difference in overall survival and more adverse events (hepatotoxicity, visual disturbances) with voriconazole. Established voriconazole as an effective option for HSCT prophylaxis, with the choice between voriconazole and fluconazole depending on individual risk factors for Aspergillus vs Candida.",sourceIds:["wingard-2010-voriconazole"]}],riskFactors:"Host factors increasing FN risk and severity: Type of malignancy (AML/ALL highest risk, lymphoma/multiple myeloma intermediate, solid tumors variable), chemotherapy regimen intensity and myelosuppressive potential, duration of expected neutropenia (>7 days = prolonged = high risk), age >65, ECOG performance status ≥2, mucositis severity (NCI grade ≥2 = viridans streptococcal risk + oral route contraindicated), comorbidities (COPD, cardiac disease, diabetes), prior FN or fungal infection, indwelling central venous catheters (gram-positive bacteremia risk), prior antibiotic/antifungal exposure (resistance selection), malnutrition and poor functional status. Regimen-specific risk: CHOP → ~10–15% FN; R-CHOP → 15–20%; Docetaxel-containing → 20–40%; AML induction (7+3) → >80%; ICE, ESHAP → >20%; high-dose cyclophosphamide + stem cell mobilization → high risk. Patient-specific risk modifiers: Hepatic or renal dysfunction impairs antibiotic clearance; prior antibiotic prophylaxis with fluoroquinolones may select for resistant organisms."},subcategories:[{id:"low-risk-fn",name:"Low-Risk Febrile Neutropenia",definition:"Low-risk FN is defined by MASCC score ≥21 (predicted serious complication rate <10%, mortality <1%) OR CISNE score 0 (complication rate ~1.1%) in solid tumor outpatients who appear clinically stable. These patients are candidates for oral antibiotic therapy and, in selected cases, outpatient management. Key low-risk features: solid tumor (not hematologic malignancy), ANC nadir expected to be brief (<7 days), outpatient status at fever onset, no significant comorbidities, no evidence of hepatic or renal insufficiency, no hemodynamic instability, no mucositis precluding oral intake, and no indwelling catheter infection.",clinicalPresentation:"Patients with low-risk FN typically appear clinically well or only mildly ill. Fever is often the sole finding without clear source on examination. MASCC SCORE ASSESSMENT (required at triage): (1) Burden of illness: no/mild symptoms = 5 pts, moderate = 3 pts, severe/moribund = 0 pts. (2) No hypotension (SBP ≥90 mmHg) = 5 pts. (3) No COPD = 4 pts. (4) Solid tumor OR no prior invasive fungal infection (in hematologic malignancy) = 4 pts. (5) Outpatient status at fever onset = 3 pts. (6) No dehydration requiring IV fluids = 3 pts. (7) Age <60 years = 2 pts. Maximum score = 26. Score ≥21 = LOW RISK. CISNE SCORE (for solid tumor outpatients): ECOG PS ≥2 (2 pts), stress-induced hyperglycemia (2 pts), COPD (1 pt), cardiovascular disease (1 pt), NCI mucositis grade ≥2 (1 pt), monocytes <200/μL (1 pt). CISNE 0 = very low risk; CISNE 1–2 = low-intermediate; CISNE ≥3 = high risk. Physical exam: assess for focal infection source (sinuses, oral mucosa, pharynx, lung auscultation, skin including catheter sites, perirectal area — avoid digital rectal exam in neutropenic patients).",diagnostics:"MINIMUM WORKUP FOR ALL FN PATIENTS (regardless of risk): (1) Blood cultures — obtain AT LEAST 2 sets (4 bottles) before starting antibiotics. If central line present: 1 set from each catheter lumen AND 1 peripheral set (differential time-to-positivity >2 hours supports CLABSI). (2) CBC with differential — confirm ANC, assess platelet count (bleeding risk during procedures). (3) Comprehensive metabolic panel — assess renal and hepatic function (guides antibiotic dosing). (4) Urinalysis + urine culture. (5) Chest X-ray — if respiratory symptoms present; not required for all low-risk patients. (6) Additional cultures directed by symptoms (sputum, wound). LOW-RISK SPECIFIC: After initial IV evaluation and culture collection, low-risk patients (MASCC ≥21, CISNE 0, clinically stable) may be transitioned to oral therapy. IDSA 2010 recommends a period of IV observation in the ED or clinic (2–4 hours minimum) before oral step-down. Patients must meet ALL criteria before oral/outpatient management: afebrile for ≥1h after acetaminophen/NSAIDs, hemodynamically stable, tolerating oral intake, reliable patient/caregiver, prompt return access if deterioration, and close follow-up within 24 hours.",durationGuidance:{standard:"Continue until ANC ≥500 cells/μL AND afebrile for ≥48 hours. Minimum 3 days of antibiotics even if ANC recovers and fever resolves sooner. For low-risk patients with negative cultures who defervesce promptly: IDSA 2010 supports de-escalation to observation (without antibiotics) when ANC ≥500 cells/μL after ≥5–7 days of therapy in clinically well patients.",stewardshipNote:"IDSA 2010 (Strong, A-I): Low-risk patients who meet outpatient criteria can be managed entirely with oral antibiotics as outpatients after initial ED/clinic assessment and 2–4 hours of IV observation. Oral ciprofloxacin + amoxicillin-clavulanate is the recommended regimen. Avoid oral monotherapy with fluoroquinolone alone if the patient received fluoroquinolone prophylaxis (high risk of breakthrough on same class). Antibiotic stewardship in FN includes early oral step-down, de-escalation with culture-directed therapy, and avoiding unnecessary antifungal escalation without evidence of fungal infection."},empiricTherapy:[{line:"First-Line — Oral Outpatient (IDSA 2010, A-I for low-risk)",options:[{drug:"cipro-amox-clav",regimen:"Ciprofloxacin 500–750 mg PO q12h + Amoxicillin-Clavulanate 875/125 mg PO q12h",notes:"IDSA 2010 (Evidence: A-I). The STANDARD oral regimen for low-risk FN. Evidence basis: Freifeld et al. NEJM 1999 RCT. Ciprofloxacin provides antipseudomonal and gram-negative coverage; amoxicillin-clavulanate adds streptococcal coverage (viridans streptococcal risk from mucositis) and broadens spectrum. CRITICAL: This combination is essential — ciprofloxacin monotherapy is INADEQUATE (poor streptococcal coverage; viridans streptococcal bacteremia from mucositis can be rapidly fatal). Duration: continue until ANC ≥500 and afebrile ≥48h. IMPORTANT CAVEAT: If patient received fluoroquinolone prophylaxis, do NOT use ciprofloxacin as empiric therapy — consider IV antipseudomonal beta-lactam instead (risk of breakthrough infection with resistant organisms).",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/low-risk-fn/first-line-oral-outpatient-idsa-2010-a-i-for-low/cipro-amox-clav-1"},{drug:"levofloxacin-oral",regimen:"Levofloxacin 750 mg PO daily (if ciprofloxacin + amox-clav not tolerated)",notes:"Alternative for patients who cannot tolerate the combination regimen. Levofloxacin 750 mg daily provides broader spectrum than ciprofloxacin alone, including better streptococcal coverage. However, FDA fluoroquinolone safety label (2016): boxed warnings for tendinopathy, peripheral neuropathy, CNS effects, and aortic aneurysm — use with appropriate clinical judgment. SAME CAVEAT: do not use if patient was on fluoroquinolone prophylaxis. Evidence: B-II (IDSA 2010).",evidence:"B-II",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/low-risk-fn/first-line-oral-outpatient-idsa-2010-a-i-for-low/levofloxacin-oral-2"}]},{line:"Initial IV (If Cannot Immediately Discharge — Observe and Step Down)",options:[{drug:"cefepime-initial",regimen:"Cefepime 2g IV q8h × first 2–4 hours during ED/clinic evaluation, then step down to oral if criteria met",notes:"For low-risk patients presenting to ED who are started on IV empirically: initiate cefepime or pip-tazo IV while cultures are collected and risk stratification is completed. If MASCC ≥21 and all outpatient criteria met after 2–4h of observation → transition to oral ciprofloxacin + amoxicillin-clavulanate. Do not delay oral step-down for low-risk patients who meet criteria. IV continuation not required and increases healthcare costs and risks (line infections, hospital-acquired complications).",evidence:"B-II",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/low-risk-fn/initial-iv-if-cannot-immediately-discharge-obser/cefepime-initial-1"}]},{line:"Beta-Lactam Allergy — Low Risk",options:[{drug:"aztreonam-fn",regimen:"Aztreonam 2g IV q8h + Vancomycin 15–20 mg/kg IV q8–12h (for severe penicillin allergy precluding all beta-lactams)",notes:"For patients with documented severe IgE-mediated penicillin allergy where cross-reactivity with cephalosporins is a concern. Aztreonam provides gram-negative (including Pseudomonas) coverage. Add vancomycin for gram-positive coverage. Note: cross-reactivity between penicillin and cephalosporins is <1–2% in patients with confirmed penicillin allergy (sIgE to penicillin determinants). Most 'penicillin-allergic' patients can safely receive cefepime — consider allergy reconciliation before defaulting to aztreonam-based regimens.",evidence:"B-III",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/low-risk-fn/beta-lactam-allergy-low-risk/aztreonam-fn-1"}]}],organismSpecific:[{organism:"Gram-Negative Bacteremia (E. coli, Klebsiella, Pseudomonas aeruginosa)",preferred:"De-escalate to pathogen-directed therapy based on susceptibilities. Pseudomonas: cefepime 2g IV q8h, pip-tazo 4.5g IV q6h, or meropenem 1g IV q8h. E. coli/Klebsiella (susceptible): ceftriaxone 2g IV daily or ciprofloxacin 500mg PO BID.",alternative:"Ciprofloxacin 400mg IV q12h (gram-negative, ciprofloxacin-susceptible). For ESBL producers: meropenem 1g IV q8h or ertapenem 1g IV daily.",notes:"Gram-negative bacteremia — though less frequent than gram-positives in the modern era — carries the highest mortality in FN (up to 30–50% in Pseudomonas BSI). Pseudomonas aeruginosa is the most feared pathogen: rapidly fatal if empiric coverage is delayed or inadequate. Any delay in appropriate antipseudomonal therapy >1–2 hours markedly worsens outcomes. Blood culture results typically return in 12–24h — adjust therapy immediately upon identification and susceptibility data. ESBL-producing E. coli and Klebsiella are increasingly common in FN patients with prior antibiotic exposure — know your institution's local rates."},{organism:"Viridans Group Streptococci (S. mitis, S. oralis, S. salivarius)",preferred:"Penicillin G 2–4 million units IV q4–6h OR ampicillin 2g IV q4h (if MIC ≤0.12 mcg/mL). Ceftriaxone 2g IV daily if intermediate penicillin susceptibility.",alternative:"Vancomycin 15–20 mg/kg IV q8–12h (AUC-guided) for penicillin-resistant isolates or anaphylaxis to beta-lactams. Linezolid 600mg IV/PO BID (salvage).",notes:"Viridans streptococci are the most common cause of gram-positive bacteremia in FN, particularly in patients with severe mucositis (NCI grade ≥3) from high-dose chemotherapy (AML induction, HSCT conditioning). The mucositis disrupts the oral mucosal barrier, allowing normal oropharyngeal flora to translocate. S. mitis and S. oralis can cause particularly severe sepsis syndrome (ARDS, multiorgan failure) in this setting — often called 'streptococcal toxic shock.' Penicillin resistance rates have increased (up to 25–30% in some institutions). This is the primary reason ciprofloxacin alone is NEVER adequate for low-risk FN — amoxicillin-clavulanate must be paired for streptococcal coverage. Antifungal prophylaxis (posaconazole) does NOT reduce viridans streptococcal risk."},{organism:"Coagulase-Negative Staphylococci (CoNS — S. epidermidis, S. haemolyticus)",preferred:"Vancomycin 15–20 mg/kg IV q8–12h (AUC/MIC target 400–600) if definitive CoNS bacteremia from a reliable culture source confirmed.",alternative:"Daptomycin 6–8 mg/kg IV daily if vancomycin intolerance or MIC creep. Linezolid 600mg IV/PO BID.",notes:"CoNS are the most common blood culture isolate in FN patients, but also the most common contaminant. A single positive bottle in a stable patient may represent contamination — wait for repeat culture positivity (≥2 sets) before committing to full vancomycin therapy. IDSA 2010 recommends AGAINST routine empiric vancomycin — add vancomycin for suspected CoNS bacteremia only when: multiple positive culture bottles from separate venipunctures, clinically deteriorating patient, or positive from peripheral blood AND catheter with differential time to positivity. OPAT with vancomycin IV or oral linezolid may be appropriate after catheter source assessment."},{organism:"Staphylococcus aureus (MSSA)",preferred:"Cefazolin 2g IV q8h (preferred over nafcillin — equivalent efficacy, less toxicity, q8h dosing for OPAT).",alternative:"Nafcillin 2g IV q4h or oxacillin 2g IV q4h if cefazolin unavailable. Dicloxacillin 500mg PO QID for oral step-down (limited data in FN).",notes:"MSSA is an uncommon but serious cause of FN bacteremia, usually from catheter or skin sources. De-escalate from vancomycin to cefazolin immediately upon MSSA identification — vancomycin is INFERIOR to beta-lactams for MSSA (slower bacteremia clearance, higher mortality). This de-escalation step is one of the highest-impact stewardship interventions in FN management. Evaluate for complications: endocarditis workup (TTE/TEE) if >3 days bacteremia, follow-up blood cultures to document clearance."}],pearls:["MASCC SCORE ≥21 IS REQUIRED — NOT OPTIONAL — before discharging a FN patient on oral antibiotics. Do not rely on clinical gestalt alone. Calculate the score explicitly and document it. Patients who 'look fine' but score <21 need IV therapy and inpatient management.","CIPROFLOXACIN ALONE IS NEVER ADEQUATE FOR LOW-RISK FN. The critical teaching point: oral ciprofloxacin has poor activity against viridans streptococci. Mucositis (common in chemotherapy patients) breaks down the oral mucosal barrier, allowing viridans streptococci to enter the bloodstream. Without the amoxicillin-clavulanate component, you will miss this pathogen. Always prescribe the combination.","FLUOROQUINOLONE PROPHYLAXIS CHANGES THE EMPIRIC APPROACH: If a patient was receiving FQ prophylaxis (ciprofloxacin or levofloxacin) and develops FN, do NOT use a fluoroquinolone as empiric therapy. These patients are at high risk for breakthrough bacteremia with FQ-resistant organisms (ESBL-producing Enterobacterales, resistant Pseudomonas). Use an antipseudomonal beta-lactam instead.","OUTPATIENT FN CRITERIA ARE STRICT — ALL MUST BE MET: (1) MASCC ≥21 AND CISNE 0–2, (2) Clinically stable (afebrile after antipyretics, SBP ≥90, HR <100, RR <20, O2 sat normal), (3) Tolerating oral medications, (4) No evidence of active infection source requiring IV access, (5) Reliable patient/caregiver with phone contact, (6) Access to emergency care within 1 hour, (7) Follow-up appointment within 24 hours arranged. Missing even one criterion = inpatient IV therapy.","24-HOUR FOLLOW-UP IS NON-NEGOTIABLE FOR OUTPATIENT FN. The 'window of risk' is the first 24–48 hours when cultures may turn positive and clinical deterioration can occur rapidly. A phone check at 12 hours + in-person reassessment at 24 hours is the minimum standard. Give patients explicit return precautions (worsening fever, rigors, hypotension, confusion, dyspnea) and ensure they understand to return IMMEDIATELY.","DO NOT ROUTINELY OBTAIN CHEST IMAGING IN ASYMPTOMATIC LOW-RISK FN. IDSA 2010: CXR is not required for all FN patients — reserve for those with respiratory symptoms (cough, dyspnea, desaturation). Routine CXR in asymptomatic FN has very low yield and adds cost/radiation. High-resolution CT chest is preferred over plain film when pulmonary infection is clinically suspected in the neutropenic host."],diagnosticWorkup:{status:"ready",summary:"Document MASCC/CISNE logic, obtain cultures before antibiotics when feasible, and confirm that mucositis, GI absorption, and social follow-up truly support outpatient oral treatment."},severitySignals:{status:"ready",summary:"Any hypotension, organ dysfunction, pneumonia, abdominal pain, severe mucositis, or unstable comorbidity removes the patient from a low-risk FN pathway."},mdroRiskFactors:{status:"ready",summary:"Recent fluoroquinolone prophylaxis, prior ESBL or Pseudomonas, resistant gram-positive colonization, and prolonged recent admissions should push therapy away from routine outpatient oral regimens."},sourceControl:{status:"ready",summary:"Inspect lines, oral mucosa, skin, perirectal area, and the GI tract early because the physical source may be subtle in neutropenia."},deEscalation:{status:"ready",summary:"If cultures stay negative and the patient remains clinically stable, avoid escalating solely because fever persists through the first neutropenic day or two."},ivToPoPlan:{status:"ready",summary:"This pathway is already designed for oral therapy when absorption is reliable; switch to inpatient IV therapy promptly if mucositis, vomiting, or instability develops."},failureEscalation:{status:"ready",summary:"Escalate quickly for recurrent fever, culture growth, worsening mucositis, or any hint that outpatient follow-up will not be reliable."},consultTriggers:{status:"ready",summary:"Oncology and ID input are appropriate when prophylaxis failure or resistant-organism history undermines standard low-risk assumptions."},durationAnchor:{status:"ready",summary:"Tie duration to documented infection when found; for culture-negative FN, stop according to recovery and institutional oncologic protocols rather than arbitrary long courses."}},{id:"high-risk-fn",name:"High-Risk Febrile Neutropenia",definition:"High-risk FN is defined by MASCC score <21, OR anticipated prolonged neutropenia (ANC <100 cells/μL expected for >7 days), OR profound neutropenia (ANC <100 cells/μL), OR significant comorbidities (hepatic/renal insufficiency, hemodynamic instability, uncontrolled malignancy), OR hematologic malignancy with active disease, OR allogeneic HSCT recipients. ALL high-risk patients require IMMEDIATE hospitalization and empiric IV antipseudomonal antibiotic therapy (within 60 minutes of triage). Any delay in appropriate empiric therapy in high-risk FN is directly associated with increased mortality — particularly for gram-negative bacteremia where the window for intervention is narrow.",clinicalPresentation:"High-risk patients may present with frank sepsis (hypotension, tachycardia, altered mentation, organ dysfunction) or with isolated fever and profound neutropenia (ANC <100) without obvious sepsis physiology — do not be reassured by a 'stable' appearance in the context of ANC <100. INITIAL ASSESSMENT: (1) Vital signs — any hemodynamic instability mandates immediate IV antibiotics + fluid resuscitation. (2) Oropharyngeal exam — grade mucositis (NCI grade 1–4): Grade 1 = erythema; Grade 2 = patchy ulcerations; Grade 3 = confluent ulcerations, unable to eat solid food; Grade 4 = tissue necrosis, unable to eat or drink. Grade ≥3 = viridans streptococcal risk + oral route CONTRAINDICATED. (3) Catheter sites — examine all lumens, tunneled catheter exit sites, and implanted port sites for erythema, discharge, tenderness. (4) Lung exam — new crackles or consolidation. (5) Skin — any eschars, purpuric lesions (bacteremia), necrotic skin (mold infection). (6) Abdomen — typhlitis (neutropenic enterocolitis): RLQ pain/tenderness in neutropenic patient = emergency; CT abdomen required. CALCULATE MASCC SCORE EXPLICITLY. Document ANC nadir, expected duration of neutropenia, and prior antibiotic/antifungal history.",diagnostics:"MANDATORY HIGH-RISK FN WORKUP: (1) Blood cultures × ≥2 sets from EACH catheter lumen AND peripheral venipuncture — simultaneous draw, document time of draw on each bottle. Differential time to positivity (DTTP) >2h from catheter vs peripheral = CLABSI (88% sensitivity, 90% specificity). (2) CBC with differential, CMP, LFTs — baseline for dosing and toxicity monitoring. (3) Urinalysis + urine culture. (4) CXR — all high-risk patients. (5) Procalcitonin (PCT) — obtain at baseline; PCT ≥0.5 ng/mL supports bacterial infection and may guide de-escalation or discontinuation. (6) Beta-D-glucan (BDG) + galactomannan (serum) — consider for patients with prolonged neutropenia >7 days or fever persisting >4 days despite antibiotics (pre-emptive antifungal strategy). (7) Additional source-directed cultures: sputum (if cough), stool for C. difficile PCR (if diarrhea), wound/ulcer swab. (8) CT chest (HIGH-RESOLUTION) — for ANY respiratory symptoms in neutropenic patient (plain CXR misses up to 40% of pulmonary infiltrates in neutropenia). CT abdomen/pelvis — for abdominal pain (typhlitis, appendicitis, colitis). (9) Ophthalmology consultation — if candidemia suspected (endophthalmitis in 10–15%). REPEAT CULTURES: At 48–72h if fever persists or clinical deterioration; do not repeat cultures routinely every 24h without clinical indication (low yield, increases contamination rates).",durationGuidance:{standard:"Until ANC ≥500 cells/μL sustained for ≥2 consecutive days AND afebrile for ≥48 hours AND clinical improvement. Minimum 7 days for most high-risk FN episodes.",severe:"14–21 days for documented bacterial infection (organism-specific therapy from first negative blood culture). 4–6 weeks for endocarditis or osteomyelitis. Duration of antifungal therapy: ≥14 days from first negative blood culture for candidemia (document clearance); ≥6–12 weeks for invasive aspergillosis.",opatNote:"OPAT (outpatient parenteral antibiotic therapy) may be appropriate for selected HIGH-RISK patients who have clinically stabilized after 5–7 days of inpatient IV therapy, have a new ANC trend upward (>200 cells/μL), are afebrile for ≥48h, and have no ongoing catheter-related issues. Cefepime IV q8h via pump, ertapenem 1g IV daily (if Pseudomonas risk low), or other regimens may be appropriate for OPAT. Must have home health nurse access and close ID follow-up.",stewardshipNote:"ANTIBIOTIC STEWARDSHIP IN HIGH-RISK FN: (1) De-escalate from antipseudomonal coverage to narrower spectrum once culture data available and patient stabilized (e.g., E. coli bacteremia → ceftriaxone or ciprofloxacin if susceptible). (2) Discontinue vancomycin at 48–72h if no gram-positive pathogen identified and patient improving (IDSA A-II). (3) Avoid adding metronidazole or anaerobic coverage empirically unless typhlitis or intra-abdominal infection suspected. (4) Procalcitonin-guided de-escalation: PCT <0.5 ng/mL (or >80% decline from peak) supports antibiotic discontinuation in afebrile, neutrophil-recovering patients. (5) Pre-emptive vs empiric antifungal strategy: using BDG/galactomannan to guide antifungal initiation rather than fever duration alone reduces unnecessary antifungal exposure by 20–30% without compromising outcomes."},empiricTherapy:[{line:"Monotherapy — Antipseudomonal Beta-Lactam (IDSA 2010 First-Line, A-I)",options:[{drug:"cefepime",regimen:"Cefepime 2g IV q8h",notes:"IDSA 2010 preferred first-line monotherapy (A-I). Fourth-generation cephalosporin with excellent antipseudomonal activity and broad gram-negative + gram-positive spectrum. Does NOT cover MRSA, Enterococcus, or anaerobes. DOSING NOTE: 2g q8h is the standard for FN; continuous infusion (6g over 24h by elastomeric pump) has pharmacodynamic advantages for organisms with higher MICs. RENAL DOSING: CrCl 30–60 → 1–2g q12h; CrCl 11–29 → 1–2g q24h; HD → 0.5–1g after each HD session. CNS TOXICITY RISK: neurotoxicity (encephalopathy, myoclonus, seizures) at higher exposures — especially in renal failure. Monitor closely in elderly and renally impaired patients. Consider EEG if altered mental status develops on cefepime.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",plan:{regimen:"Cefepime 2g IV q8h",indication:"High-risk febrile neutropenia",site:"Systemic",role:"preferred",rationale:"Standard first-line high-risk FN monotherapy when shock, abdominal source, or prior ESBL history does not force a broader backbone.",pathogenFocus:["Pseudomonas","Common gram-negative FN pathogens","Viridans streptococci"],riskFactorTriggers:["High-risk FN without dominant abdominal source","Need frontline antipseudomonal beta-lactam"],avoidIf:["Typhlitis or anaerobic source without added coverage","Prior ESBL or MDR gram-negative bacteremia"],renalFlags:["Renal adjustment and neurotoxicity monitoring are essential in prolonged therapy"],linkedMonographIds:["cefepime"]},monographId:"cefepime",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/monotherapy-antipseudomonal-beta-lactam-idsa-201/cefepime-1"},{drug:"piperacillin-tazobactam",regimen:"Piperacillin-Tazobactam 4.5g IV q6h (or 3.375g IV q6h for less severe)",notes:"IDSA 2010 alternative first-line monotherapy (A-I). Broad-spectrum: antipseudomonal + anaerobic coverage + good gram-positive activity. Particularly advantageous when typhlitis, perirectal infection, or intra-abdominal source is suspected (anaerobic coverage included). Standard dosing: 4.5g IV q6h; extended infusion (3-hour infusion of 3.375g q8h or 4.5g q8h) pharmacodynamically superior for organisms with higher MICs — consider for critically ill patients or when Pseudomonas susceptibility is borderline. RENAL DOSING: CrCl 20–40 → 3.375g q8h; CrCl <20/HD → 2.25g q8h (additional 0.75g after HD). GALACTOMANNAN FALSE POSITIVES: pip-tazo can cause false-positive serum galactomannan — interpret serum GM cautiously in patients on pip-tazo; BAL GM preferred if pulmonary aspergillosis suspected.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",plan:{regimen:"Piperacillin-Tazobactam 4.5g IV q6h",indication:"High-risk febrile neutropenia",site:"Systemic",role:"preferred",rationale:"High-risk FN backbone when typhlitis, perirectal infection, or another anaerobic abdominal source is part of the picture.",pathogenFocus:["Pseudomonas","Enterobacterales","Anaerobes"],riskFactorTriggers:["Abdominal pain or suspected typhlitis","Perirectal or intra-abdominal source","Need anaerobic coverage without a second agent"],avoidIf:["Strong ESBL history makes meropenem cleaner","Unnecessary nephrotoxin stacking with vancomycin"],renalFlags:["Extended infusion and dose adjustment matter in unstable kidney function"],linkedMonographIds:["pip-tazo"]},evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/monotherapy-antipseudomonal-beta-lactam-idsa-201/piperacillin-tazobactam-2"},{drug:"meropenem",regimen:"Meropenem 1g IV q8h (2g IV q8h for Pseudomonas or suspected resistant organisms)",notes:"IDSA 2010 alternative first-line monotherapy (A-I). Reserve as the broadest coverage option — covers Pseudomonas, ESBL producers, AmpC producers, anaerobes, streptococci. Preferred as empiric first-line in: (1) Patients with prior gram-negative bacteremia due to ESBL-producing organisms, (2) Recent hospitalization in regions with high ESBL prevalence, (3) Clinically unstable or septic shock presentations where broadest coverage is critical, (4) Suspected typhlitis or abdominal source. STEWARDSHIP NOTE: Carbapenems should not be used routinely as first-line when cefepime or pip-tazo are appropriate — carbapenem overuse drives carbapenem-resistant Enterobacterales (CRE) emergence. RENAL DOSING: CrCl 26–50 → 1g q12h; CrCl 10–25 → 500mg q12h; CrCl <10/HD → 500mg q24h.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",plan:{regimen:"Meropenem 1g IV q8h (2g IV q8h for Pseudomonas or suspected resistant organisms)",indication:"High-risk febrile neutropenia",site:"Systemic",role:"preferred",rationale:"Broadest frontline FN beta-lactam when ESBL history, septic shock, or severe abdominal source makes cefepime or pip-tazo too narrow.",pathogenFocus:["ESBL Enterobacterales","Pseudomonas","Anaerobes"],riskFactorTriggers:["Prior ESBL bacteremia","Septic shock","Typhlitis with severe instability"],avoidIf:["Culture history supports cefepime or pip-tazo exit"],renalFlags:["Dose around kidney function and renal replacement from the first day"],linkedMonographIds:["meropenem"]},monographId:"meropenem",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/monotherapy-antipseudomonal-beta-lactam-idsa-201/meropenem-3"}]},{line:"ADD Vancomycin — Only If Specific Indications Present (IDSA 2010, A-I)",options:[{drug:"vancomycin-fn",regimen:"Vancomycin 25–30 mg/kg IV loading dose (actual body weight, max 3g), then 15–20 mg/kg IV q8–12h (AUC/MIC target 400–600 mcg·h/mL using Bayesian software)",notes:"IDSA 2010 (A-I): Vancomycin should NOT be routinely added to empiric FN therapy. Evidence shows routine addition of vancomycin does NOT improve outcomes, increases nephrotoxicity risk, and prolongs therapy duration unnecessarily. ADD VANCOMYCIN ONLY FOR THE FOLLOWING INDICATIONS: (1) Clinically apparent catheter-related infection (exit site erythema/discharge, tunneled catheter tenderness, positive blood cultures flagging from catheter before peripheral). (2) Skin or soft tissue infection (cellulitis, wound infection). (3) Hemodynamic instability or suspected septic shock (broader empiric coverage until source identified). (4) Blood cultures positive for gram-positive organisms (add while awaiting species ID and susceptibilities). (5) Suspected mucositis-associated viridans streptococcal sepsis (NCI grade 3–4 mucositis + severe sepsis picture). (6) Known MRSA colonization with new pulmonary infiltrates or bacteremia. REASSESSMENT AT 48–72H: Discontinue vancomycin if no gram-positive pathogen isolated and patient improving (A-II). AUC-GUIDED DOSING: 2020 ASHP/IDSA/SIDP consensus guidelines mandate AUC/MIC 400–600 monitoring over trough-based dosing — use Bayesian software (e.g., InsightRx, Vanderbilt AUC calculator).",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",plan:{regimen:"Vancomycin 25-30 mg/kg IV loading dose, then AUC/MIC-guided maintenance dosing",indication:"High-risk FN with gram-positive or line-risk trigger",site:"Systemic",role:"adjunct",rationale:"Reserved FN add-on for catheter, skin and soft tissue, shock, or culture-based gram-positive signals rather than routine default use.",pathogenFocus:["MRSA","Resistant viridans streptococci","Serious catheter-related gram-positive infection"],riskFactorTriggers:["Hemodynamic instability","Clinically apparent catheter infection","Skin or soft tissue infection","Gram-positive blood culture signal"],avoidIf:["No gram-positive indication after 48-72 hours"],renalFlags:["AUC-guided dosing and nephrotoxin review are mandatory"],rapidDiagnosticActions:["Stop early if cultures do not show a target gram-positive pathogen"],linkedMonographIds:["vancomycin"]},evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/add-vancomycin-only-if-specific-indications-pres/vancomycin-fn-1"}]},{line:"ADD Metronidazole — For Suspected Anaerobic/Intra-Abdominal Source",options:[{drug:"metronidazole-fn",regimen:"Metronidazole 500mg IV q8h (or 1g IV q12h for extended infusion)",notes:"Add anaerobic coverage when: (1) Typhlitis (neutropenic enterocolitis) — RLQ pain + fever in neutropenic patient; CT-confirmed bowel wall thickening. (2) Perirectal abscess (do NOT perform digital rectal exam — can introduce bacteremia; use imaging). (3) Intra-abdominal source (diverticulitis, appendicitis). (4) Oral/dental source with suspected anaerobic involvement. NOTE: Piperacillin-tazobactam already has anaerobic coverage — metronidazole is redundant and should NOT be added if pip-tazo is the backbone agent. Add metronidazole only when cefepime or meropenem is used as the primary antipseudomonal agent in suspected anaerobic infection.",evidence:"B-III",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",plan:{regimen:"Metronidazole 500mg IV q8h",indication:"High-risk FN with anaerobic source concern",site:"Intra-abdominal",role:"adjunct",rationale:"Add only when cefepime or meropenem needs anaerobic help for typhlitis or perirectal infection; do not duplicate pip-tazo anaerobe coverage.",pathogenFocus:["Bacteroides and other anaerobes"],riskFactorTriggers:["Typhlitis","Perirectal infection","Oral anaerobic source"],avoidIf:["Piperacillin-tazobactam is already the backbone"],linkedMonographIds:["metronidazole"]},evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/add-metronidazole-for-suspected-anaerobic-intra-/metronidazole-fn-1"}]},{line:"ADD Antifungal — Persistent Fever >4–7 Days Despite Antibiotics",options:[{drug:"micafungin-fn",regimen:"Micafungin 100–150 mg IV daily (echinocandin preferred if Candida suspected)",notes:"EMPIRIC ANTIFUNGAL: Add after 4–7 days of persistent fever despite adequate antibacterial therapy, in the setting of prolonged neutropenia. Echinocandin (micafungin, caspofungin, anidulafungin) preferred when: (1) Prior azole exposure or prophylaxis, (2) Hemodynamic instability, (3) Candida species unknown. Micafungin 100 mg daily (standard); 150 mg daily for higher-risk patients (obese, hematologic malignancy, critically ill). PRE-EMPTIVE STRATEGY: Many centers now use BDG and serum galactomannan at day 4–5 of persistent fever to guide antifungal initiation rather than fever duration alone — this reduces unnecessary antifungal therapy by 20–30% without compromising outcomes. BDG >80 pg/mL or serum GM >0.5 ODI supports antifungal initiation. Duration: minimum 14 days for candidemia from first negative blood culture; 6–12 weeks for invasive aspergillosis.",evidence:"A-I (Walsh 2004 trial)",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/add-antifungal-persistent-fever-4-7-days-despite/micafungin-fn-1"},{drug:"voriconazole-fn",regimen:"Voriconazole 6 mg/kg IV q12h × 2 loading doses, then 4 mg/kg IV q12h; OR 200 mg PO q12h (if able to take orally)",notes:"PREFERRED when Aspergillus (or other mold) is suspected: CT chest showing halo sign, nodules, or cavitary lesions; prolonged neutropenia >10 days; HSCT recipient. Voriconazole covers Aspergillus fumigatus, A. flavus, A. niger (but NOT Mucorales). THERAPEUTIC DRUG MONITORING mandatory: target trough 1.0–5.5 mcg/mL. Supratherapeutic levels → hepatotoxicity, visual disturbances, encephalopathy. Subtherapeutic → treatment failure. SIGNIFICANT DRUG INTERACTIONS: inhibits CYP2C19, CYP2C9, CYP3A4 — major interactions with tacrolimus (reduce dose 66%), cyclosporine (reduce dose 50%), sirolimus (CONTRAINDICATED), carbamazepine, rifampin, phenytoin. Avoid in patients with CrCl <50 if using IV formulation (cyclodextrin vehicle accumulates; switch to PO).",evidence:"A-I (for suspected aspergillosis)",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/add-antifungal-persistent-fever-4-7-days-despite/voriconazole-fn-2"},{drug:"liposomal-amphotericin-fn",regimen:"Amphotericin B liposomal (AmBisome) 3 mg/kg IV daily",notes:"FOR EMPIRIC ANTIFUNGAL when echinocandin and azole are both contraindicated, or when Mucorales (mucormycosis) is suspected (CT chest showing reverse halo sign, rhinocerebral extension). Voriconazole has NO Mucorales activity — use amphotericin B or isavuconazole for suspected mucormycosis. NEPHROTOXICITY MONITORING: daily BMP (creatinine, potassium, magnesium, sodium). Pre-hydration with 1L NS reduces nephrotoxicity. Hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia are nearly universal — supplement aggressively. Avoid concurrent nephrotoxins (vancomycin, aminoglycosides, calcineurin inhibitors) when possible.",evidence:"A-I (Walsh 1999 trial)",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/add-antifungal-persistent-fever-4-7-days-despite/liposomal-amphotericin-fn-3"}]},{line:"ADD MRSA Coverage — Specific High-Risk Scenarios",options:[{drug:"vancomycin-mrsa-fn",regimen:"Vancomycin IV (AUC/MIC 400–600) — see dosing above",notes:"ADD vancomycin for MRSA-specific coverage in: (1) Hemodynamic instability (septic shock) — until source clarified. (2) Skin or soft tissue infection (SSTI) with MRSA risk factors. (3) Central catheter infection with purulence/tunnel tract involvement. (4) Prior MRSA colonization or infection. (5) Chest CT showing necrotizing pneumonia or cavitary lesion consistent with MRSA. Discontinue at 48–72h if no MRSA/gram-positive pathogen confirmed. AUC-guided dosing is the standard — do not use trough-only monitoring.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/add-mrsa-coverage-specific-high-risk-scenarios/vancomycin-mrsa-fn-1"},{drug:"daptomycin-fn",regimen:"Daptomycin 6–10 mg/kg IV daily (higher doses for bacteremia/endocarditis)",notes:"ALTERNATIVE to vancomycin for gram-positive/MRSA coverage when: vancomycin MIC ≥2 (vancomycin heteroresistance), vancomycin nephrotoxicity, prior vancomycin failure, or concurrent nephrotoxic drug combinations. CONTRAINDICATED for pneumonia — daptomycin is inactivated by pulmonary surfactant. Monitor CPK weekly (myopathy risk, especially at higher doses). No need for TDM, but CPK monitoring essential.",evidence:"B-II",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/add-mrsa-coverage-specific-high-risk-scenarios/daptomycin-fn-2"}]},{line:"Aminoglycoside — Do NOT Use as Routine Combination (A-I, Not Recommended)",options:[{drug:"amikacin-fn",regimen:"Amikacin 15–20 mg/kg IV once daily (extended-interval dosing) — ONLY if specific documented resistance scenario",notes:"IDSA 2010 (A-I): Aminoglycoside combination therapy with antipseudomonal beta-lactams is NOT recommended for routine FN empiric therapy. No mortality benefit from combination in RCTs; significantly higher nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity with combination therapy. SPECIFIC INDICATIONS (narrow): (1) Documented gram-negative bacteremia with resistant organism susceptible only to aminoglycoside + another agent (e.g., CRE with limited options), (2) Suspected Pseudomonas with carbapenem resistance and aminoglycoside susceptibility confirmed. Extended-interval dosing (15–20 mg/kg once daily) is standard; goal peak 56–64 mcg/mL and trough <1 mcg/mL (gentamicin/tobramycin: 5–7 mg/kg daily, peak 20–30, trough <1). Avoid in patients with CrCl <60 — dose adjustment required and toxicity risk high.",evidence:"A-I (not recommended routinely)",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/aminoglycoside-do-not-use-as-routine-combination/amikacin-fn-1"}]},{line:"G-CSF — Adjunctive Therapy for Selected High-Risk FN",options:[{drug:"filgrastim-fn",regimen:"Filgrastim (G-CSF) 5 mcg/kg/day SC (round to nearest vial: 300 mcg or 480 mcg) until ANC ≥1000–2000 cells/μL post-nadir; OR Pegfilgrastim 6 mg SC × 1 dose (NOT for acute FN treatment — prophylaxis only)",notes:"IDSA/ASCO G-CSF GUIDANCE: Therapeutic G-CSF (during FN episode) is recommended for patients with HIGH-RISK features: (1) Expected prolonged neutropenia >10 days, (2) Age >65, (3) Uncontrolled/progressive malignancy, (4) Documented pneumonia, septic shock, or invasive fungal infection, (5) Prior FN episode. G-CSF shortens duration of neutropenia by 1–3 days and reduces infectious complications. NOT universally recommended for all FN — low-risk patients with expected rapid ANC recovery do not clearly benefit. PEGFILGRASTIM TIMING: If patient received pegfilgrastim ≤14 days before current FN episode, the depot effect may still be active — check timing before re-administering. PRIMARY PROPHYLAXIS: Filgrastim or pegfilgrastim recommended when FN risk from chemotherapy regimen is ≥20%. SECONDARY PROPHYLAXIS: After a prior FN episode, G-CSF in subsequent cycles maintains dose intensity.",evidence:"A-I (high-risk features)",evidenceSource:"NCCN 2024",evidenceSourceIds:["nccn-fever-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/high-risk-fn/g-csf-adjunctive-therapy-for-selected-high-risk-/filgrastim-fn-1"}]}],organismSpecific:[{organism:"Pseudomonas aeruginosa Bacteremia",preferred:"Cefepime 2g IV q8h (or pip-tazo 4.5g IV q6h) based on susceptibilities. If MDR Pseudomonas: meropenem 2g IV q8h (extended infusion 3h) + consider polymyxin B or ceftolozane-tazobactam if carbapenem-resistant.",alternative:"Ciprofloxacin 400mg IV q8h (if susceptible, and as de-escalation option). Ceftazidime-avibactam 2.5g IV q8h for carbapenem-resistant isolates with KPC or OXA-48 (NOT MBL). Ceftolozane-tazobactam 1.5g IV q8h for MDR Pseudomonas (MBL-producing strains).",notes:"Pseudomonas bacteremia carries the highest mortality of any organism in FN (up to 30–50%) — the primary reason antipseudomonal beta-lactams are first-line empiric therapy. Any delay in appropriate coverage is directly associated with mortality. DEFINITIVE THERAPY: Select the narrowest effective agent based on susceptibility data. Combination therapy (beta-lactam + FQ or aminoglycoside) is NOT superior to monotherapy with active agents in most clinical studies for non-ICU patients, but some experts prefer double coverage for severe Pseudomonas bacteremia or endocarditis. Monitor blood cultures for clearance. Echocardiography if bacteremia persists >3–5 days."},{organism:"ESBL-Producing E. coli or Klebsiella pneumoniae",preferred:"Meropenem 1g IV q8h (definitive therapy for ESBL bacteremia). Ertapenem 1g IV daily (acceptable for non-Pseudomonas ESBL bacteremia once stable — OPAT-friendly).",alternative:"Ceftazidime-avibactam 2.5g IV q8h if KPC-producing carbapenem-resistant Klebsiella (CRKp). Temocillin (European) for non-CNS/non-ESBL bacteremia if available. Fosfomycin (UTI only) or nitrofurantoin (UTI only) for ESBL urinary tract sources if susceptible.",notes:"ESBL-producing Enterobacterales are increasingly common in FN patients with prior healthcare exposure, prior fluoroquinolone prophylaxis, or travel to endemic regions. Carbapenems are the definitive treatment — cefepime is UNRELIABLE for ESBL bacteremia (inoculum effect, heteroresistance). Do NOT use third-generation cephalosporins (ceftriaxone, cefotaxime) for ESBL infections even if susceptibility testing shows 'susceptible.' Pip-tazo clinical outcomes data for ESBL bacteremia is conflicting — MERINO trial showed meropenem superior to pip-tazo for ESBL bacteremia (mortality 12.3% vs 3.7%, p=0.90 — actually substantially lower mortality with meropenem) — carbapenem is preferred for bacteremia. OPAT consideration: ertapenem 1g IV daily is a convenient once-daily option suitable for OPAT once patient is stable."},{organism:"Klebsiella pneumoniae Carbapenemase (KPC)-Producing CRE",preferred:"Ceftazidime-avibactam 2.5g IV q8h (first-line for KPC, OXA-48). Consider combination with aztreonam for MBL (metallo-beta-lactamase) producers (aztreonam 2g IV q6h + ceftazidime-avibactam for NDM/VIM/IMP).",alternative:"Meropenem-vaborbactam 4g IV q8h (3-hour infusion) for KPC-producing CRE. Imipenem-cilastatin-relebactam 1.25g IV q6h for KPC-producing CRE. Polymyxin B 1.25–1.5 mg/kg IV q12h in combination with meropenem or fosfomycin (salvage only).",notes:"CRE in FN carries mortality of 40–70% — one of the most feared pathogens in neutropenic oncology patients. INSTITUTIONAL AWARENESS: Know your hospital's CRE resistance mechanisms (KPC vs MBL vs OXA) — this determines which beta-lactam/beta-lactamase inhibitor combination is active. For NDM/VIM/IMP (MBL producers): ceftazidime-avibactam has NO MBL activity alone — combine with aztreonam. Rapid molecular testing (Verigene, BioFire) can identify resistance mechanisms from positive blood cultures within 2–4 hours — collaborate with pharmacy to ensure results are acted on immediately."},{organism:"Staphylococcus aureus MRSA — Catheter or Skin Source",preferred:"Vancomycin IV (AUC/MIC 400–600) — full SAB workup (follow-up cultures q24–48h, TTE/TEE, ID consult). Duration: minimum 14 days for uncomplicated SAB from first negative blood culture; 4–6 weeks for endocarditis.",alternative:"Daptomycin 8–10 mg/kg IV daily (for vancomycin MIC ≥2, intolerance, or persistent bacteremia on vancomycin). Ceftaroline 600mg IV q8h + daptomycin (salvage for persistent MRSA bacteremia).",notes:"MRSA SAB in neutropenic patients requires the same comprehensive workup as MRSA SAB in non-neutropenic patients — it is never a 'simple' line infection. Remove the central venous catheter as soon as possible (within 24–48h if attributable to line). Follow-up blood cultures every 24–48 hours until documented clearance — date of first negative blood culture is Day 1 of duration. ID consultation reduces mortality by 40–50% in SAB. Do NOT add rifampin to vancomycin for native-site MRSA bacteremia — ARREST trial showed no benefit and increased drug interactions."},{organism:"Enterococcus faecium (VRE) Bacteremia",preferred:"Daptomycin 6–10 mg/kg IV daily ± ampicillin (if ampicillin-susceptible, rare for E. faecium). Linezolid 600mg IV/PO BID (bacteriostatic — less preferred for bacteremia).",alternative:"For selected stable patients with VRE UTI source: nitrofurantoin or fosfomycin (non-bacteremic only). Quinupristin-dalfopristin (Q/D) for E. faecium only (NOT E. faecalis) — significant myalgia, hepatotoxicity; rarely used.",notes:"VRE bacteremia mortality in neutropenic patients is 25–40%. Source identification and control is critical (GI/rectal reservoir, perianal abscess, compromised GI mucosa). High-dose daptomycin (8–10 mg/kg) recommended for VRE bacteremia. If daptomycin MIC is rising (≥4 mcg/mL): consider daptomycin + ampicillin combination (paradoxically, ampicillin increases VRE susceptibility to daptomycin even in ampicillin-resistant strains by disrupting cell wall synthesis and enhancing daptomycin membrane binding). Linezolid is bacteriostatic — myelosuppression risk with prolonged use in already cytopenics patients; reserve for salvage or oral step-down."},{organism:"Candida Species (Candidemia in Neutropenic Host)",preferred:"Micafungin 100 mg IV daily (first-line, IDSA 2016 echinocandin recommendation). Caspofungin 70 mg IV load × 1, then 50 mg IV daily. Anidulafungin 200 mg IV load × 1, then 100 mg IV daily.",alternative:"Liposomal amphotericin B 3–5 mg/kg IV daily (for echinocandin resistance, CNS candidiasis, or C. auris with resistance). Fluconazole 800 mg IV/PO load × 1, then 400 mg IV/PO daily (de-escalation for C. albicans/tropicalis after identification and susceptibility confirm — NOT initial empiric).",notes:"Candidemia in neutropenic patients requires the same workup as non-neutropenic candidemia: (1) Repeat blood cultures every 24–48h until clearance — duration 14 days from first negative. (2) CVC removal (within 24–48h) reduces mortality. (3) Ophthalmology exam (after neutrophil recovery — funduscopy unreliable in severe neutropenia due to lack of inflammatory response). (4) Echocardiography if prolonged candidemia. C. parapsilosis: echinocandin MICs are higher (intrinsic FKS polymorphism) — de-escalate to fluconazole once species confirmed and patient stable. C. glabrata: maintain echinocandin, obtain FKS mutation testing if prior echinocandin exposure. C. auris: contact precautions, echinocandin preferred (MDR, often FQ/fluconazole resistant)."}],pearls:["ANTIBIOTICS WITHIN 60 MINUTES IN HIGH-RISK FN. This is not a goal — it is the standard. Mortality doubles for every hour of delay in appropriate empiric antibiotics for gram-negative bacteremia in neutropenia. Triage nurses and pharmacists must recognize FN as a sepsis-level emergency. If the pharmacy cannot dispense cefepime within 30 minutes of the order, escalate the process.","ANTIPSEUDOMONAL BETA-LACTAM MONOTHERAPY IS THE STANDARD — NOT DOUBLE COVERAGE. Decades of RCT data show combination therapy (e.g., cefepime + aminoglycoside, pip-tazo + vancomycin empirically) does NOT improve outcomes and increases toxicity. Monotherapy with cefepime, pip-tazo, or meropenem provides equivalent efficacy with less nephrotoxicity, less selection pressure, and simpler management. Resist the urge to add 'extra coverage' empirically.","VANCOMYCIN IS NOT PART OF ROUTINE EMPIRIC FN THERAPY. The IDSA 2010 guideline is explicit: routine empiric vancomycin does not improve outcomes in FN. It should be added ONLY for specific indications (catheter infection, skin/soft tissue infection, hemodynamic instability, gram-positive on rapid blood culture identification). Unnecessary vancomycin = nephrotoxicity + drug interactions + resistance selection. Set a 48–72h automatic stop order or reassessment.","CEFEPIME NEUROTOXICITY — KNOW THE RISK. Cefepime encephalopathy (confusion, myoclonus, nonconvulsive status epilepticus) is underrecognized and can be misattributed to metabolic encephalopathy, opioids, or disease progression. Risk factors: AKI, reduced CrCl (accumulation), older age, pre-existing CNS pathology. If an FN patient develops altered mental status on cefepime, check renal function, dose, and consider EEG. This is a pharmacist-critical monitoring point.","TYPHLITIS (NEUTROPENIC ENTEROCOLITIS) IS A SURGICAL AND MEDICAL EMERGENCY. RLQ pain in a neutropenic patient = presumptive typhlitis until proven otherwise. Obtain urgent CT abdomen/pelvis. Broaden antibiotic coverage to include anaerobes (metronidazole + pip-tazo or meropenem alone). Surgical consultation is essential — perforation is a life-threatening complication. Do NOT perform digital rectal exam — bacteremia risk. Serial abdominal exams every 4–6h in hospitalized neutropenic patients with abdominal symptoms.","G-CSF IN ACTIVE FN: Therapeutic G-CSF (filgrastim 5 mcg/kg/day SC) accelerates ANC recovery in high-risk FN but does NOT reduce mortality in most RCTs. Reserve for specific high-risk features: expected prolonged neutropenia >10 days, septic shock, pneumonia, invasive fungal infection, age >65, or progressive disease. Don't use G-CSF therapeutically for all FN episodes — the ASCO guidelines are clear that routine use in all FN patients is not recommended. PRIMARY PROPHYLAXIS is where G-CSF has the strongest evidence (≥20% FN risk)."],diagnosticWorkup:{status:"ready",summary:"Blood cultures from every lumen plus peripheral blood, baseline labs, focused imaging, and review of prophylaxis history should happen immediately alongside first-dose IV therapy."},severitySignals:{status:"ready",summary:"Hypotension, pneumonia, abdominal pain/typhlitis, altered mentation, or expected prolonged neutropenia define this as a high-risk pathway from the start."},mdroRiskFactors:{status:"ready",summary:"Prior fluoroquinolone prophylaxis, prior ESBL or resistant Pseudomonas, recent broad-spectrum exposure, and long inpatient oncology courses are the critical empiric resistance gates."},sourceControl:{status:"ready",summary:"Inspect lines, mucositis, perirectal disease, abdominal catastrophe, and pulmonary sources early; neutropenic sepsis can look source-poor until you look hard."},deEscalation:{status:"ready",summary:"At 48-72 hours, narrow only when cultures and clinical course genuinely support it, but do not leave empiric vancomycin or carbapenem coverage in place without an ongoing reason."},ivToPoPlan:{status:"ready",summary:"PO completion is rare until hemodynamics stabilize, GI absorption is reliable, and the recovered organism/site clearly fits an oral agent."},failureEscalation:{status:"ready",summary:"Persistent fever requires re-exam, repeat imaging, fungal risk review, and line/source reassessment instead of endless broad-spectrum stacking."},consultTriggers:{status:"ready",summary:"ID is high yield in prolonged fever, prior resistant-organism history, suspected typhlitis, invasive fungal concern, or unclear de-escalation timing."},durationAnchor:{status:"ready",summary:"Duration should follow the documented infection plus neutrophil recovery logic of the syndrome; avoid carrying empiric broad IV therapy far beyond what the source actually requires."},rapidDiagnostics:[{trigger:"Blood culture or rapid molecular result shows resistant gram-negative risk such as ESBL or prior CRE history",action:"Escalate from cefepime or pip-tazo to a carbapenem or phenotype-directed reserve agent without waiting for another fever day.",rationale:"In high-risk FN, resistant gram-negative delay is the microbiology failure most likely to become catastrophic quickly."},{trigger:"No line, skin, pneumonia, or hemodynamic indication for MRSA coverage emerges after initial cultures",action:"Stop empiric vancomycin early instead of carrying it through the entire neutropenic episode.",rationale:"Routine vancomycin continuation adds nephrotoxicity and line burden without improving most high-risk FN outcomes."}],breakpointNotes:[{marker:"Cefepime susceptibility in neutropenic sepsis",interpretation:"The result assumes full-dose 2 g q8h exposure, ideally with optimized infusion timing in unstable patients.",action:"If fever or bacteremia persists, check whether the PK strategy failed before concluding the organism needs another class."},{marker:"Persistent fever without microbiologic growth",interpretation:"Ongoing fever alone does not prove resistant bacteria and should not automatically trigger endless antibacterial broadening.",action:"Reassess for fungal disease, mucositis, typhlitis, line issues, or a nonbacterial driver at the 4-7 day mark."}],intrinsicResistance:[{organism:"Enterococcus species",resistance:"Cefepime and other cephalosporins are intrinsically inactive against Enterococcus.",implication:"If the line, abdomen, or urinary tract strongly suggests Enterococcal infection, pick a regimen that actually covers it."},{organism:"Bacteroides fragilis group",resistance:"Cefepime lacks reliable anaerobic coverage.",implication:"Add metronidazole or choose another backbone when typhlitis, perirectal infection, or another anaerobic source is suspected."}],coverageMatrix:[{label:"Usual high-risk FN gram-negative pathogens including Pseudomonas",status:"preferred",detail:"Cefepime, pip-tazo, or meropenem remain the frontline anchors while cultures are pending."},{label:"MRSA or resistant gram-positive line infection",status:"conditional",detail:"Vancomycin is an add-on for specific indications rather than a default companion drug for every high-risk FN patient."},{label:"ESBL or major resistant gram-negative history",status:"conditional",detail:"Meropenem becomes the cleaner anchor when prior microbiology makes cefepime or pip-tazo unsafe."},{label:"Early empiric antifungal therapy on day 1",status:"avoid",detail:"Reserve antifungal escalation for persistent fever, prolonged neutropenia, or host and imaging signals that make invasive fungal disease credible."}]},{id:"fn-with-fungal-risk",name:"Febrile Neutropenia — Persistent / Fungal Risk",definition:"Persistent FN is defined as ongoing fever despite 4–7 days of adequate broad-spectrum antibacterial therapy, with negative or inconclusive bacterial cultures, in a neutropenic patient. This pattern strongly suggests an occult infection — most critically invasive fungal infection (IFI). IFI is the leading cause of infectious mortality in patients with prolonged neutropenia (ANC <500 for >10 days). The two dominant pathogens are Candida species (especially in HSCT recipients and patients with prolonged IV access/TPN) and Aspergillus species (especially in AML patients, allogeneic HSCT, and patients receiving high-dose corticosteroids). Empiric antifungal therapy is added at day 4–7, or earlier if: suggestive CT chest findings (halo sign, nodules), rising beta-D-glucan (BDG), positive serum galactomannan, or clinical deterioration.",clinicalPresentation:"Persistent fever in the neutropenic host after 4–7 days of antibacterial therapy, without an identified bacterial source. Clinical clues to fungal infection: PULMONARY: new onset cough, pleuritic chest pain, hemoptysis (Aspergillus — angioinvasive), dyspnea (PCP, diffuse candidiasis); CT CHEST: halo sign (ground-glass opacity surrounding a pulmonary nodule = early angioinvasive aspergillosis), air crescent sign (late finding, appearing with neutrophil recovery as necrotic tissue separates), reverse halo/atoll sign (suggests mucormycosis or organizing pneumonia), multiple bilateral nodules (hematogenous fungal dissemination). SINUS: nasal congestion, facial pain, epistaxis, periorbital swelling (Aspergillus sinusitis), black eschar on nasal mucosa (mucormycosis — a true emergency requiring urgent surgical debridement). SKIN: erythematous papules/nodules with central pallor (disseminated candidiasis), necrotic skin lesions (disseminated Aspergillus). HEPATOSPLENIC (CHRONIC DISSEMINATED) CANDIDIASIS: fever persisting AFTER ANC recovery, elevated ALP, 'bull's eye' lesions on CT/MRI of liver and spleen — occurs when neutrophils finally recover and mount inflammatory response against established Candida foci. OCULAR: candida endophthalmitis — white fluffy vitreous infiltrates on funduscopy (painful visual changes + FN + positive blood culture = urgent ophthalmology). BDG AND GALACTOMANNAN: BDG >80 pg/mL supports IFI diagnosis (sensitive but non-specific — false positives from pip-tazo, dialysis, beta-glucan-containing foods, Streptococcal bacteremia); galactomannan >0.5 ODI (serum) or >1.0 ODI (BAL) supports invasive aspergillosis. Serial monitoring twice weekly in high-risk patients increases sensitivity.",diagnostics:"FUNGAL DIAGNOSTIC WORKUP IN PERSISTENT FN: (1) CT Chest (HIGH-RESOLUTION): MANDATORY at day 4–5 of persistent fever despite antibiotics. Plain CXR has 40–60% sensitivity for pulmonary fungal infection in neutropenic patients — CT is required. Look for: halo sign (early IPA), air crescent sign (late IPA), reverse halo (mucormycosis), nodules, consolidation, cavitation. (2) Serum Galactomannan (GM): Obtain twice weekly in high-risk patients (AML, allogeneic HSCT). Sensitivity 60–80% for IPA in hematologic malignancy (lower in solid tumors, SOT, and non-neutropenic patients). FALSE POSITIVES: piperacillin-tazobactam (less common with newer formulations but still occurs), cross-reactivity with Histoplasma, Blastomyces, Penicillium, Fusarium, Alternaria; dietary sources (some pasta, cereals). (3) Serum Beta-D-Glucan (BDG): Twice weekly in high-risk prolonged neutropenia. Non-specific: elevated in Candida, Aspergillus, PCP, Fusarium — does NOT detect Mucorales (no glucan in cell wall). (4) BAL (Bronchoalveolar Lavage): If CT chest abnormality and patient can tolerate bronchoscopy (platelets >50k, no severe coagulopathy). BAL GM ≥1.0 ODI has higher specificity than serum; fungal culture, bacterial culture, PCP PCR, viral PCR (CMV, HHV-6, RSV, rhinovirus). (5) CT Sinuses/Neck: For sinus symptoms — early mucormycosis requires CT (bony erosion, extension to orbit or brain). (6) Ophthalmology Exam: For suspected candidemia — schedule after neutrophil recovery in neutropenic patients (funduscopic exam is unreliable during severe neutropenia). (7) Serum Cryptococcal Antigen (CrAg): For HSCT recipients or HIV-positive patients with meningeal symptoms or unexplained FN. (8) PCR-Based Assays: Aspergillus PCR (blood or BAL) — increasing validation as adjunct diagnostic; now an EORTC/MSG mycologic criterion. T2Candida Panel: rapid multiplex PCR from blood (3–5 hours) detecting 5 most common Candida species with sensitivity 91%, specificity 98% — useful for early species identification in suspected candidemia.",durationGuidance:{standard:"Empiric antifungal therapy: Continue until ANC ≥500 cells/μL for ≥2 days AND clinically well AND no documented fungal infection (can discontinue empiric antifungal without documented IFI if afebrile + ANC recovering). Documented candidemia: 14 days from FIRST NEGATIVE blood culture. Documented invasive aspergillosis: minimum 6–12 weeks, individualized based on immune status and radiographic response.",severe:"Invasive aspergillosis in HSCT/AML: 6–12 weeks minimum, often continued through subsequent immunosuppressive cycles as secondary prophylaxis. Mucormycosis: surgical debridement + amphotericin B ≥6 weeks (or until all necrotic tissue debrided and immune reconstitution achieved). Chronic disseminated candidiasis (hepatosplenic): azole therapy (fluconazole 400–800 mg daily) for ≥6 months or until all lesions resolved on imaging.",opatNote:"OPAT for antifungal therapy: Voriconazole (200 mg PO BID) and fluconazole (400–800 mg PO daily) have excellent oral bioavailability (>96% and ~90%, respectively) — transition to oral as soon as patient can take oral medications. Micafungin and other echinocandins are IV only — rezafungin (once-weekly echinocandin, FDA approved 2023) may enable less frequent IV dosing for OPAT-eligible patients with candidemia. Isavuconazole (372 mg PO daily — once-daily dosing) is a convenient option for Aspergillus OPAT.",stewardshipNote:"ANTIFUNGAL STEWARDSHIP IN FN: (1) Pre-emptive vs empiric antifungal: using BDG/GM biomarkers and CT findings to guide antifungal initiation (pre-emptive strategy) rather than fever duration alone reduces unnecessary antifungal exposure by 20–30% without compromising outcomes — implement in high-risk institutions. (2) Echinocandin-to-azole de-escalation: transition from echinocandin to oral fluconazole (C. albicans, C. tropicalis) or oral voriconazole/isavuconazole (Aspergillus) once species identified, patient stable, and cultures clearing. (3) IV-to-PO conversion: voriconazole and fluconazole have near-complete oral bioavailability — switch to oral the moment patient can swallow. (4) Antifungal prophylaxis review: ongoing prophylaxis with posaconazole 300 mg daily after AML induction reduces IFI by 75% — ensure appropriate patients are on posaconazole prophylaxis BEFORE the next chemotherapy cycle. (5) Duration limits: empiric antifungals without documented IFI should be discontinued when ANC recovers and fever resolves; no need to continue for an arbitrary fixed duration."},empiricTherapy:[{line:"Antifungal Prophylaxis — AML/MDS (Prevention Before FN Episode)",options:[{drug:"posaconazole-prophylaxis",regimen:"Posaconazole Delayed-Release Tablet (DRT) 300 mg PO daily (load 300 mg BID × 1 day) — PREFERRED over suspension",notes:"IDSA 2010 + NCCN 2024 (Category 1): Posaconazole is the PREFERRED antifungal prophylaxis for AML/MDS patients receiving induction or salvage chemotherapy expected to result in prolonged neutropenia (>7 days). Evidence: Cornely et al. NEJM 2007 — posaconazole reduced IFI (2% vs 8%, p<0.001) and invasive aspergillosis (1% vs 7%, p<0.001) vs fluconazole/itraconazole. DRUG FORMULATION MATTERS: Delayed-release tablet achieves more reliable PK than the suspension (suspension requires high-fat meal and acidic pH for absorption — unreliable in mucositis). Check TDM: target trough ≥0.5–0.7 mcg/mL for prophylaxis (obtain within first week). MAJOR DRUG INTERACTIONS: posaconazole is a strong CYP3A4 inhibitor — increases tacrolimus, cyclosporine, sirolimus, midazolam, statins, vincristine (vincristine neurotoxicity!). Avoid coadministration with rifampin, carbamazepine, phenytoin (reduce posaconazole levels by 80%). CHECK QTCF: posaconazole prolongs QTc — avoid with other QT-prolonging agents if possible.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/antifungal-prophylaxis-aml-mds-prevention-before/posaconazole-prophylaxis-1"},{drug:"fluconazole-prophylaxis",regimen:"Fluconazole 400 mg PO/IV daily (for allogeneic HSCT — engraftment through day +75; for patients with lower IPA risk)",notes:"Fluconazole prophylaxis is recommended for allogeneic HSCT recipients during the engraftment phase (conditioning through day +75 or longer if prolonged neutropenia). Evidence: multiple RCTs demonstrating reduction in candidiasis and candidemia mortality. LIMITATION: NO ASPERGILLUS ACTIVITY — fluconazole does not prevent invasive mold infections. In centers with high Aspergillus prevalence or for patients receiving intensive conditioning (matched unrelated donor, cord blood, haploidentical), posaconazole or voriconazole is preferred. Fluconazole is appropriate for standard myeloablative HSCT in centers with low Aspergillus incidence.",evidence:"A-I (for HSCT engraftment phase)",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/antifungal-prophylaxis-aml-mds-prevention-before/fluconazole-prophylaxis-2"},{drug:"voriconazole-prophylaxis",regimen:"Voriconazole 200 mg PO q12h (avoid high-fat meals; TDM trough target 1.0–5.5 mcg/mL)",notes:"Voriconazole prophylaxis for allogeneic HSCT recipients with high Aspergillus risk (unrelated donor, cord blood, significant GVHD, prolonged steroid use). Evidence: Wingard et al. Blood 2010 — reduced invasive aspergillosis vs fluconazole (1.5% vs 3%, p=0.02) in allogeneic HSCT. Comparable aspergillosis prevention to posaconazole with less favorable tolerability (visual disturbances, hepatotoxicity, phototoxicity, QTc effects). TDM mandatory. IMPORTANT: voriconazole has NO Mucorales activity — if mucormycosis is a concern, choose posaconazole or liposomal amphotericin B. Breakthrough mucormycosis on voriconazole prophylaxis has been reported.",evidence:"B-I",evidenceSource:"NCCN 2024",evidenceSourceIds:["nccn-fever-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/antifungal-prophylaxis-aml-mds-prevention-before/voriconazole-prophylaxis-3"}]},{line:"Antibacterial Prophylaxis — High-Risk Prolonged Neutropenia",options:[{drug:"ciprofloxacin-ppx",regimen:"Ciprofloxacin 500 mg PO BID — for expected neutropenia >7 days (AML induction, HSCT)",notes:"IDSA 2010 (A-I): Fluoroquinolone prophylaxis reduces FN incidence by 50% and infection-related mortality in patients expected to have prolonged profound neutropenia. NCCN 2024 recommends fluoroquinolone prophylaxis for: neutropenia expected >7 days (AML induction, intensive lymphoma regimens, HSCT). CRITICAL CAVEATS: (1) Increased FQ resistance — widespread prophylaxis selects for FQ-resistant gram-negatives (especially ESBL-producing E. coli). If FN develops while on FQ prophylaxis, use IV antipseudomonal beta-lactam (NOT a fluoroquinolone). (2) C. difficile risk — FQ prophylaxis increases CDI risk; concomitant proton pump inhibitors further increase risk. Monitor for diarrhea. (3) QTc effects if combined with azole antifungals. Levofloxacin 500 mg PO daily is an alternative — CALGB 10403 and other trials show similar efficacy to ciprofloxacin.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/antibacterial-prophylaxis-high-risk-prolonged-ne/ciprofloxacin-ppx-1"}]},{line:"Empiric Antifungal — Persistent Fever Day 4–7 (If Candida Pattern Suspected)",options:[{drug:"micafungin-empiric",regimen:"Micafungin 100–150 mg IV daily",notes:"PREFERRED empiric antifungal at 4–7 days of persistent FN when: Candida is more likely than Aspergillus (shorter neutropenia duration, solid tumor, prior candidiasis, no new CT chest findings), prior azole prophylaxis use, hemodynamically unstable patient (avoid azoles until stable). Evidence: Walsh et al. NEJM 2004 (caspofungin non-inferior to liposomal AmB). Broad Candida spectrum; NO activity against Aspergillus or Mucorales. Once Candida species identified and susceptibility confirmed: de-escalate to fluconazole 400 mg PO daily if fluconazole-susceptible and patient stable.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/empiric-antifungal-persistent-fever-day-4-7-if-c/micafungin-empiric-1"},{drug:"caspofungin-empiric",regimen:"Caspofungin 70 mg IV × 1 load, then 50 mg IV daily",notes:"Alternative echinocandin for empiric antifungal in persistent FN. FDA-approved indication for empiric antifungal in FN (the only echinocandin with this labeled indication, though all are used). Evidence: Walsh 2004 NEJM trial compared caspofungin vs liposomal AmB — caspofungin was non-inferior with better tolerability. More drug interactions than micafungin or anidulafungin (cyclosporine — hepatotoxicity; rifampin — reduces caspofungin levels requiring 70 mg daily maintenance dose). Hepatic dose adjustment: Child-Pugh B → 35 mg daily after load.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/empiric-antifungal-persistent-fever-day-4-7-if-c/caspofungin-empiric-2"}]},{line:"Empiric/Pre-emptive Antifungal — Persistent Fever + Mold Risk (CT Chest Abnormality or Galactomannan Positive)",options:[{drug:"voriconazole-empiric-fn",regimen:"Voriconazole 6 mg/kg IV q12h × 2 loading doses, then 4 mg/kg IV q12h; transition to 200 mg PO q12h when stable. TDM trough target 1.0–5.5 mcg/mL.",notes:"PREFERRED for suspected invasive aspergillosis (halo sign on CT, positive galactomannan, prolonged neutropenia >10 days, HSCT recipient, high-dose corticosteroids). Evidence: IDSA 2016 aspergillosis guidelines — voriconazole first-line for IPA. MONITORING: obtain first trough on day 5; check LFTs, visual symptoms, and QTc weekly. MAJOR INTERACTIONS: inhibits CYP2C19/2C9/3A4 — reduce tacrolimus by 66%, cyclosporine by 50%; CONTRAINDICATED with sirolimus, rifampin, carbamazepine. IV formulation contains cyclodextrin vehicle — accumulates in CrCl <50; switch to oral PO if renal impairment develops.",evidence:"A-I (for suspected IPA)",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/empiric-pre-emptive-antifungal-persistent-fever-/voriconazole-empiric-fn-1"},{drug:"isavuconazole-empiric-fn",regimen:"Isavuconazonium sulfate (CRESEMBA) 372 mg (= 200 mg isavuconazole) IV/PO q8h × 6 doses over 48 hours (loading phase), then 372 mg IV/PO daily",notes:"ALTERNATIVE to voriconazole for suspected IPA with advantages: (1) No QTc prolongation (shortens QTc — avoid in short QT syndrome), (2) IV without cyclodextrin — safe in all levels of renal impairment, (3) Less visual disturbances, (4) Covers Mucorales (unlike voriconazole) — preferred when diagnosis uncertain between aspergillosis and mucormycosis, (5) Once-daily dosing after load, (6) More predictable pharmacokinetics (TDM less critical but still recommended). Evidence: SECURE trial (Maertens 2016) — non-inferior to voriconazole for primary IPA therapy. NCCN 2024: isavuconazole is preferred by many hematology centers as first-line for IPA due to better tolerability profile.",evidence:"A-I (non-inferior to voriconazole)",evidenceSource:"NCCN 2024",evidenceSourceIds:["nccn-fever-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/empiric-pre-emptive-antifungal-persistent-fever-/isavuconazole-empiric-fn-2"},{drug:"liposomal-amphotericin-empiric-fn",regimen:"Amphotericin B liposomal (AmBisome) 3 mg/kg IV daily (increase to 5 mg/kg for CNS or severe disease; 5–10 mg/kg for mucormycosis)",notes:"FOR EMPIRIC ANTIFUNGAL: When azoles cannot be used (severe drug interactions, hepatotoxicity, azole-resistant organism suspected) or when Mucorales is the primary concern (CT showing reverse halo sign, sinus/palatal involvement, rhinocerebral extension). WALSH 1999 TRIAL: liposomal AmB equivalent to conventional AmB for empiric FN antifungal with less nephrotoxicity (19% vs 34% creatinine doubling) and fewer infusion reactions. NEPHROTOXICITY MANAGEMENT: Pre-hydrate with 1L NS before each infusion. Aggressive electrolyte replacement (hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia are near-universal). Monitor daily BMP. Avoid concurrent nephrotoxins. Target K+ ≥3.5, Mg2+ ≥1.8 with IV replacement as needed.",evidence:"A-I",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/empiric-pre-emptive-antifungal-persistent-fever-/liposomal-amphotericin-empiric-fn-3"}]},{line:"Mucormycosis — Surgical Emergency + Antifungal",options:[{drug:"liposomal-amphotericin-mucor",regimen:"Amphotericin B liposomal 5–10 mg/kg IV daily + Urgent surgical debridement + Reverse immunosuppression (reduce steroids, manage hyperglycemia, correct acidosis)",notes:"MUCORMYCOSIS IS A SURGICAL AND MEDICAL EMERGENCY. Any delay in surgical debridement (including rhinosinusitis, orbital involvement, cutaneous necrotizing infection) worsens prognosis dramatically. ANTIFUNGAL: High-dose liposomal AmB (5 mg/kg minimum; some centers use 7.5–10 mg/kg for CNS or disseminated disease). Posaconazole (300 mg PO/IV daily) or isavuconazole (372 mg daily after loading) are step-down options after clinical improvement and surgery. VORICONAZOLE IS INEFFECTIVE AGAINST MUCORALES — do not use. CT imaging of sinuses, orbits, and brain is mandatory. PET/CT may define extent of disease. Correct all predisposing factors: hyperglycemia, acidosis (DKA predisposes), iron overload (deferasirox has in vitro anti-Mucorales activity; clinical benefit uncertain), reduce steroids as much as oncologically acceptable. Adjunctive hyperbaric oxygen — limited data, center-specific.",evidence:"A-II (AmB) + surgical (mandatory)",evidenceSource:"IDSA 2010",evidenceSourceIds:["idsa-febrile-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/mucormycosis-surgical-emergency-antifungal/liposomal-amphotericin-mucor-1"}]},{line:"PCP (Pneumocystis jirovecii Pneumonia) — Prophylaxis and Treatment",options:[{drug:"tmp-smx-pcp",regimen:"TMP-SMX (Bactrim DS) 1 DS tablet (160/800 mg) PO daily OR 1 SS tablet daily OR 1 DS tablet PO TIW — PROPHYLAXIS. TMP-SMX 15–20 mg/kg/day IV (of TMP component) divided q6–8h — TREATMENT",notes:"PCP PROPHYLAXIS: Required for patients on ≥20 mg/day of prednisone equivalent for ≥1 month, patients with CD4 <200 (HIV+), HSCT recipients (through day +180 or longer with ongoing immunosuppression), patients receiving temozolomide, fludarabine, or other T-cell depleting agents. TMP-SMX is first-line prophylaxis — also provides prophylaxis against Toxoplasma and bacterial infections. ALTERNATIVES for TMP-SMX intolerance: Dapsone 100 mg PO daily (check G6PD first), atovaquone 1500 mg PO daily with fatty food, inhaled pentamidine 300 mg monthly via Respigard nebulizer. TREATMENT of confirmed PCP: TMP-SMX 15–20 mg/kg/day IV × 21 days + prednisone 40 mg BID × 5 days then taper (if PaO2 <70 mmHg or A-a gradient >35). TOXICITY: Myelosuppression, renal impairment, hypersensitivity (rash, fever, SJS — rare). Monitoring: CBC weekly, CMP.",evidence:"A-I (prophylaxis)",evidenceSource:"NCCN 2024",evidenceSourceIds:["nccn-fever-neutropenia"],id:"febrile-neutropenia/fn-with-fungal-risk/pcp-pneumocystis-jirovecii-pneumonia-prophylaxis/tmp-smx-pcp-1"}]}],organismSpecific:[{organism:"Aspergillus fumigatus (IPA)",preferred:"Voriconazole 6 mg/kg IV q12h × 2 load doses, then 4 mg/kg IV q12h (TDM trough 1.0–5.5 mcg/mL). OR Isavuconazole 372 mg q8h × 6 doses, then 372 mg daily.",alternative:"Liposomal amphotericin B 3–5 mg/kg IV daily (if voriconazole not tolerated or azole resistance suspected). Caspofungin/micafungin (in combination or salvage — NOT monotherapy for IPA).",notes:"A. fumigatus causes >90% of invasive aspergillosis in neutropenic patients. Angioinvasive — penetrates blood vessel walls causing hemorrhagic infarction and high mortality. Triazole resistance (TR34/L98H mutation) is increasing globally (~1–3% in US, higher in Netherlands/UK) — consider if treatment failure, refractory disease, or patient traveled to high-prevalence region. Combination therapy (voriconazole + echinocandin): consider for severe/refractory IPA with high galactomannan burden — Marr et al. 2015 (subgroup with proven IPA showed mortality benefit). Minimum treatment duration: 6–12 weeks from diagnosis, individualized by immune reconstitution and radiographic response. Secondary prophylaxis recommended during subsequent immunosuppressive cycles."},{organism:"Mucor/Rhizopus (Mucormycosis)",preferred:"Liposomal amphotericin B 5–10 mg/kg IV daily + urgent surgical debridement + reverse immunosuppression + correct hyperglycemia/acidosis.",alternative:"Isavuconazole 372 mg daily (step-down or if AmB not tolerated). Posaconazole 300 mg daily (step-down after AmB induction). Amphotericin B + posaconazole or isavuconazole combination (limited data).",notes:"Mucormycosis mortality is 40–80% — early recognition and aggressive surgery are paramount. Rhinosinusitis form: black eschar on nasal mucosa, palate necrosis, proptosis, facial swelling — these are LATE signs; treat before they appear. Pulmonary form: reverse halo sign (atoll sign) on CT chest is suggestive but not pathognomonic. CRITICAL DIAGNOSTIC: tissue biopsy with culture and histopathology is required for definitive diagnosis (serum GM and BDG are NEGATIVE in mucormycosis — do not use to rule in/out). Iron availability is a key virulence factor — avoid deferoxamine (iron chelator that PROVIDES iron to Mucorales and worsens infection); deferasirox has in vitro activity but clinical benefit unproven."},{organism:"Candida albicans (Candidemia, Hepatosplenic)",preferred:"Micafungin 100 mg IV daily → de-escalate to fluconazole 400 mg PO daily after confirmation of susceptibility + clinical stability. For hepatosplenic candidiasis: fluconazole 400–800 mg PO daily × ≥6 months.",alternative:"Caspofungin or anidulafungin (alternative echinocandins). Liposomal AmB if CNS involvement.",notes:"Hepatosplenic (chronic disseminated) candidiasis presents paradoxically AFTER neutrophil recovery — rising ALP, persistent fever, and 'bull's eye' lesions on CT/MRI. The inflammatory response (neutrophil influx) unmasks existing candidal foci. Treatment requires prolonged azole therapy (minimum 6 months, until complete resolution on imaging). Do not discontinue early — relapse rates are high. IFN-γ adjunct therapy has been used in refractory cases (limited data). Liposomal AmB can be used for induction followed by fluconazole step-down."},{organism:"Pneumocystis jirovecii (PCP)",preferred:"TMP-SMX 15–20 mg/kg/day IV (of TMP component) divided q6–8h × 21 days + prednisone 40 mg BID × 5 days → 40 mg daily × 5 days → 20 mg daily × 11 days (if hypoxic: PaO2 <70 or A-a gradient >35).",alternative:"Pentamidine 4 mg/kg IV daily × 21 days (if TMP-SMX not tolerated — significant toxicity: hypoglycemia, nephrotoxicity, hypotension). Atovaquone 750 mg PO BID × 21 days (mild-moderate PCP, can take orally). Primaquine + clindamycin (mild-moderate PCP alternative).",notes:"PCP in neutropenic/immunocompromised patients presents differently from HIV-PCP: more acute onset (days not weeks), less insidious, higher oxygen requirement, more heterogeneous CT findings. BAL is the diagnostic test of choice (induced sputum has lower sensitivity in non-HIV). PCP PCR from BAL is highly sensitive but can detect colonization — interpret in clinical context. Treat any immunocompromised patient with new diffuse bilateral infiltrates and hypoxia for PCP empirically while awaiting BAL confirmation. Prophylaxis compliance monitoring is a key pharmacist role."}],pearls:["POSACONAZOLE PROPHYLAXIS IN AML: THIS IS ONE OF THE HIGHEST-IMPACT INTERVENTIONS IN FN MANAGEMENT. The 2007 NEJM trial showed posaconazole reduced IFI from 8% to 2% and improved survival in AML/MDS patients. Use the DELAYED-RELEASE TABLET (not suspension — absorption is unreliable with mucositis, vomiting, and variable gastric pH). Verify posaconazole levels if clinical concern for prophylaxis failure (target trough ≥0.5–0.7 mcg/mL). Document that the next cycle of AML induction includes posaconazole on the discharge/outpatient medication reconciliation.","GALACTOMANNAN INTERPRETATION REQUIRES CONTEXT. A positive serum GM (≥0.5 ODI) in a patient on pip-tazo may be a false positive (pip-tazo contains piperazine-based beta-lactam fragments that cross-react with the GM assay — though newer formulations have reduced this, it still occurs). Repeat GM or switch to BAL GM (more specific) if pip-tazo is the primary antibiotic. Conversely, a NEGATIVE GM does not exclude aspergillosis in patients on voriconazole or posaconazole prophylaxis (antifungals suppress galactomannan release).","BETA-D-GLUCAN FALSE POSITIVES ARE COMMON IN FN PATIENTS. BDG is elevated by: (1) IVIG or albumin infusion (contains glucan), (2) Hemodialysis (cellulose membrane), (3) TMP-SMX (Bactrim), (4) Pip-tazo, (5) Amoxicillin-clavulanate, (6) Bacteremia with Gram-positive organisms (especially Streptococcus), (7) Surgical gauze or sponges left in body cavities. A positive BDG in the context of these exposures is non-specific. BDG is most useful as a NEGATIVE PREDICTIVE test — a persistently negative BDG makes IFI unlikely (sensitivity 77–80% for candidemia, 70–90% for aspergillosis). Monitor trends, not single values.","MUCOSITIS GRADE DETERMINES ORAL ROUTE VIABILITY. NCI Mucositis Grading: Grade 1 = erythema, minimal pain, eating normally; Grade 2 = patchy ulcerations, modified diet; Grade 3 = confluent ulcerations, unable to eat solid food, IV hydration needed; Grade 4 = tissue necrosis, severe pain, unable to eat or drink, parenteral nutrition. KEY THRESHOLDS: Grade ≥2 = oral fluoroquinolone + amox-clav is not reliable (absorption unpredictable, GI transit rapid). Grade ≥2 mucositis = ORAL ROUTE CONTRAINDICATED for antibiotics; use IV. Additionally, grade ≥2 = HIGH RISK for viridans streptococcal bacteremia from mucosal translocation — vancomycin coverage should be lower threshold in this setting. Grade ≥3 mucositis = viridans streptococcal sepsis risk VERY HIGH — consider prophylactic penicillin or ampicillin in selected patients (not standard, institution-specific).","G-CSF PRIMARY PROPHYLAXIS THRESHOLDS — KNOW THESE COLD. ASCO/NCCN guidelines: G-CSF PRIMARY PROPHYLAXIS recommended when FN risk ≥20%. High-risk chemotherapy regimens (>20% FN risk): CHOP-21 (DLBCL), dose-dense AC (breast), docetaxel-based regimens, TAC (breast), FOLFOX/FOLFIRI with bevacizumab, AML induction, HSCT conditioning. Intermediate-risk (10–20%): R-CVP, CHOP-14, ABVD. For intermediate-risk patients, additional risk factors (age >65, prior chemo/RT, poor performance status, HIV, open wounds, baseline cytopenias) push into primary prophylaxis territory. PEGFILGRASTIM: preferred over filgrastim for convenience (single SC injection given 24–72h AFTER last chemotherapy dose and ≥14 days before next cycle). On-body injector allows same-day administration. Never give pegfilgrastim within 24h before chemotherapy (stimulates proliferating cells that will be killed by chemo).","FLUOROQUINOLONE PROPHYLAXIS CREATES A DIAGNOSTIC AND THERAPEUTIC DILEMMA. If a patient receives FQ prophylaxis and develops FN: (1) The causative organism may be FQ-resistant — do NOT use ciprofloxacin or levofloxacin empirically. (2) Use IV antipseudomonal beta-lactam (cefepime 2g q8h) regardless of MASCC score (cannot safely use oral FQ-based regimen). (3) Blood cultures from FQ-prophylaxis recipients have higher rates of gram-negative resistance and ESBL-producing organisms — request extended susceptibility testing. (4) C. difficile risk is increased after FQ exposure — monitor for diarrhea. This is one of the key reasons antibiotic stewardship in oncology should assess whether FQ prophylaxis is truly indicated for each individual patient."],diagnosticWorkup:{status:"ready",summary:"Review neutropenia duration, mold-active prophylaxis, chest/sinus imaging, galactomannan or beta-D-glucan context, and any pulmonary or hepatosplenic clues before declaring breakthrough fungal disease."},severitySignals:{status:"ready",summary:"Hypoxia, pleuritic chest pain, hemoptysis, hypotension, or disseminated lesions mean the fungal workup and treatment decisions need to accelerate immediately."},mdroRiskFactors:{status:"ready",summary:"Prior azole prophylaxis, prior mold infection, prolonged neutropenia, and repeated broad-spectrum exposure are the key risk signals that shape empiric antifungal choice."},sourceControl:{status:"ready",summary:"Line removal, drainage of focal collections, and tissue diagnosis when safe can be crucial because microbiology is often difficult in invasive fungal disease."},deEscalation:{status:"ready",summary:"Reassess every 48-72 hours whether the patient still fits empiric antifungal criteria or can move back to prophylaxis, especially when imaging and biomarkers stay unconvincing."},ivToPoPlan:{status:"ready",summary:"Transition to oral mold-active therapy only after the patient is stable, absorption is dependable, and the chosen agent fits the breakthrough/prophylaxis history."},failureEscalation:{status:"ready",summary:"Failure should trigger repeat imaging, drug-level review, prophylaxis exposure review, and biopsy/source discussion rather than blind antifungal layering."},consultTriggers:{status:"ready",summary:"ID plus oncology are essential here, and pulmonary/interventional teams may be needed for bronchoscopy or tissue diagnosis."},durationAnchor:{status:"not_applicable",summary:"Empiric fungal therapy duration is individualized to the documented syndrome, response, and neutrophil recovery rather than a simple short-course anchor."}}],drugMonographs:[]};export{e as FEBRILE_NEUTROPENIA};
